The Writing Center Data Analysis

1. Purpose of Report

The first purpose of this report is to analyze the 2016-2018 teaching and writing Center data and to find out possible relationships in between aspect of writing and several factors, such as: International/Domestic status, Year of studies and different assingment types.

Aspect of writing is defined by two categories: 1-include editiong and rivising 0-does not incude editing and rivising

Year of studies was defined by dividing students into 2 categories: Year 1st and 2nd Year 3rd and 4th

International/Domestic status was defined by two categories: International students Domestic students

Assingment types were defined as: “Analytical.Essay”, “Research.Essay”, “Lab.Report”, “Critical.Review”, “Literature.Review”, “Annotated.Bibliography”, “Proposal”, “Journal.Entry”, “Personal.Statement”

The second purpose of this report is to further analyze the descriptions/comments filled out by each tutor after students’ visit. We want to see if there are some possible patterns/relationships in between assignment types and frequent words the tutor used as comments using word diagrams and wordlouds. Also, we could see the top 5 frequent words and biagrams used by each tutor and each assignment type.

2.First part: aspect of writing analysis

2.1 Data cleaning

As usually, we need to clean up the data based on our needs before we can start analyze it. Cleaning assingment types: -fillter out the data that does not belong to any assignment types. -remove the rows that has any of the assignment type: outline,Other.Type,Pharmacy.Exam,Essay.Exam Cleaning degree status of students: -fillter out the non degree students who do not belong to either underclassmen or upperclassmen Cleaning tutors: -fillter out the tutors who do not have that many sesssions. Cleaning aspects of writing: -categorize aspect of writing: “Include Editing” and “Not Include Editing”

2.2 Data Description

We start analyzing data starting 2016-2017. The students are categorized by Domestic or International. Also, they are separated by level of year of study, i.e. underclassmen (1st and 2nd years) or upperclassmen (3rd year and above).

2.3 2016-2017

2.3.1 2016-2017 (Overview)

In summary, the plot below shows that in 2016-2017: 1. There were more domestic students (66%) visited writing center than the international students (33%) 2. There were more underclassmen(57%) visiting the writing center than upperclassmen(43%). 3. For both groups of students(international and domestic), more underclassmen visited the writing center than upperclassmen. 4. Under each group (international & dommestic), higher proportion of international students(53%) focused on editing than domestics(34%).

# 1st plot of report (Nationality & Level of year)

2.5 Logistic regression model

2016-2017 (Model 1: no interaction)

Since both 2016-2017 and 2017-2018 were following similar trends, we have reason to believe they will show similar pattern when implementing data analysis. Data analysis using logistic regression model seems to be more fitting, since most of the variables are categorical and our response suppose to be binary. We take our Types of assingment as a predictor. The Analytical Essay is our base variable, which we compare to the rest of the Types Of Assignment. However, we also have to check if there is an interaction effect between Year of Study and Nationality. Therefore we fit the data into two different types of model which one has interaction and one without interaction. The following is a summary of the fitted logistic regression model without interaction.

Explanation: To summarize the findings, Model 1 shows that the level of Year is significant while Model 2 does not. Moreover, the interaction term is not significant. Therefore though the interaction seems significant(P-value = 0.026480) which is marginal in this case, we may consider not to include it in our model. Perhaps, it confirms the previous findings from the frequency table that Year is indeed not significant.

Both models show that the Nationality is significant model1(P-value=7.74e-08) and model2(P-value=0.005022). International students in years 2016-2017 are e^0.78773100%=220% more likely to work on editing than withouht editing for their type of writing. Smimilarly to previous findings, we can see that working on a Lab Report type of assingment will increase the odds by e^1.27915100%=359%, while working on a Critical review will decrease the odds.

3.3 Tracking change of visits

We want to analyze how the aspect of writing changes of the multi-visit students.

This hypothethis was assessed through dividing students with multiple visits into group0(not include editing) and group1 (including editing), choosing the most frequent type of Assingment of their 1st visit for each student and observe what factors influence student’s shift between the groups.

We created 2 models: 1) model 1 for students that their 1st visit is (group0) not include editing. 2) model 2 for students that their 1st visit is (group1) including editing.

the significant factors that infuence students to change the groups are: 1) For model 1(type 1 change: changes that start with including editing): nationality 2) For model 2(type 2 change: changes that start with not including editing): nationality

Here is the list of the probability that students shift from one group to another: (international student) 1) Probability that students shifted from group1 to group0 (include editing to not include editing): 48% 2) Probability that students stayed in group0 (not include editing): 49% 3) Probability that students stayed in group1(include editing): 52% 4) Probability that students shifted from group0 to group1 (not include editing to include editing): 51%

Here is the list of the probability that students shift from one group to another: (Domestic student) 1) Probability that students shifted from group1 to group0 (include editing to not include editing): 59% 2) Probability that students stayed in group0 (not include editing): 72% 3) Probability that students stayed in group1(include editing): 41% 4) Probability that students shifted from group0 to group1 (not include editing to include editing): 28%

#tracking change of visits
# library(dplyr)
c <- c() # first obs
d <- c() # last obs
dd<-c()
change <- c()
change_type_1 <- c()
change_type_2 <- c()
count <- 1
a <- mv %>% group_by(ID,Assignment_type) %>% count() %>% filter(n > 1) # get list of a assigments with multiple visits > 1
times.visit <- a$n
mv2<- mv %>% mutate(Date=as.Date(Appt.Date, '%m/%d/%Y')) %>% group_by(ID) %>% arrange((Date)) %>% slice(1:1)
mv2 <- mv2 %>% select(Level, Nationality,ID)

c <- c()
for(i in 1:nrow(a)) {
  # source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/31528981/select-first-and-last-row-from-grouped-data
  obs <- mv %>% filter(ID == a$ID[i] & Assignment_type == a$Assignment_type[i]) %>% filter(row_number()==1 | row_number()==n())
  
  if(obs$Editing.and.revising[1] == obs$Editing.and.revising[2]) {
    change[count] <- 0
  } else {
    change[count] <- 1
  }
  
  if(obs$Editing.and.revising[1] == 0) {
    change_type_1[count] <- 0
    change_type_2[count] <- 1
  }
  else {
    change_type_1[count] <- 1
    change_type_2[count] <- 0
  }
  
  modified_obs <- obs[2,]
  modified_obs$Aspects <- obs$Aspects[1]
  
  
  #c <- rbind(c,obs[1,]) # take first visit
  dd <- rbind(dd,modified_obs) # take last
  count <- count + 1
}

4. Words clouds

In this section, we will analyze description section filled out by each tutor and get words clouds for the most frequent n-gram words list (1, 2, 3). For each n-gram words list, we will focus on: 1. Words clouds from all tutors’ comments 2. Words clouds from each tutor and each assignment type. 3. Get top 3 (or 5) most frequent controlled by each tutor and assignment type.

4.1 Text mining

We changed the format of the original data set so that it will be easier to do the words clouds analysis. The main idea is for each comments, we break in to n-gram words (1,2,3) and get rid off the word that has no meaning like(the, a, has…). And then, we sort out the top 10-20 frequent words used by each tutor, each assignment, each tutor per each assignment.

Text mining - stop words

Along with common stop words, we used this set of words: \ e.g, i.e, essay, research, bibliography, annotated, analytical, critical, review, journal, entry, lab, report, literature, review, personal, statement, proposal, research, student, paper, thesis, assignment, draft, appt, 1pm, note, draft, twc, annotated, bibliography, critical, literature, statement, personal, journal, entry, discussed, discussing, review, reviewed

Text mining - negation, modal, adverbs

We will now first observe the frequency of uncleaned text. It can be seen that Tom Robles dominates in frequency of words. Also analytical essay dominates the observations too. From this, perhaps we should look at the average number of words per observation after it is cleaned instead. Also, it was found that 34.8% of the original words were left after cleaning. Now, for the tutors it can be observed that all the tutors except for Cindy have similar median amount of words per observation. Also, it can be observed that the median number of words per observations controlled by assignment to have some variability between different assignments. On the other hand, when controlled by nationality it can be observed that both groups have a similar median number of words per observation.

# Question: Does it make sense to stem n-grams where n > 1 ??
# the token to look for 2 words.
bigram_tokens <- text_df %>% unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2)
bigram_tokens <- bigram_tokens %>%
    separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") %>%
    filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word,
           !word2 %in% stop_words$word) %>% 
    filter(!word1 %in% my_stop_words$word,
           !word2 %in% my_stop_words$word) %>% 
    filter(!word1 %in% nma_words$word,
           !word2 %in% nma_words$word)  

#Remove trailing and leading spaces and extra internal whitespace with one gsub call
bigram_tokens$word1 <- gsub("\\s+","",bigram_tokens$word1)
bigram_tokens$word2 <- gsub("\\s+","",bigram_tokens$word2)
bigram_tokens <- bigram_tokens %>% na.omit() # remove NA entries
# grep returns integer or integer(0) <- vector of length 0

#word stemming (e.g layers,layer -> layer)
bigram_tokens<-bigram_tokens %>%
      mutate_at("word1", funs(wordStem((.), language="en"))) %>% mutate_at("word2", funs(wordStem((.), language="en")))

#cleans all numeric numbers in description
bigram_tokens <- bigram_tokens[-grep("\\b\\d+\\b", bigram_tokens$word1),] #word1
bigram_tokens <- bigram_tokens[-grep("\\b\\d+\\b", bigram_tokens$word2),] #word2

#unite bigram with space
bigrams_united <- bigram_tokens %>% unite(bigram, word1, word2,sep=" ")
